  <h4><a name="BILLING_POLICIES"></a>BILLING POLICIES</h4>
  <p>Unless a student withdraws from the Suzuki Violin Program completely, a student will be charged for tuition every month, regardless of the amount of participation.  The tuition remains the same regardless of the number of lessons received in a given month.  Given the three-on-one-off schedule, students may have four lessons instead of three in those months with five weeks.  <strong>Tuition remains the same.  No additional lesson fees apply.</strong>  Conversely but less frequently, in certain months (months with major holidays, for example) students may have less than three private and/or group lessons.  Again, monthly tuition remains the same regardless of the number of lessons received in a given month.  <strong>A late fee</strong> ($6 per student per month overdue) will be charged of any family that does not pay the expected amount by the first Monday of each month. </p>
  <p><em>Lessons will be discontinued if tuition is two months overdue. Lessons will resume once the balance has been paid in full.</em></p>

  <h4><a name="CANCELLATION_POLICIES"></a>CANCELLATION POLICIES</h4>
    <h5><a name="Cancellation_by_the_Student"></a>Cancellation by the Student</h5>
  <ul>
    <li>
    <strong>GROUP CLASSES</strong>
    <p>Should you and your child choose to miss a group class during any week, please give your group class teacher as much advance notice as possible (Email is always good).  Unexplained absence from group classes undermines the power of our work and demoralizes other members of the class.  If the teacher can inform the class that your child's absence was caused by an illness, a flat tire, or an annual family trip, the class will understand the absence not as lack of interest or that the absentee is letting them down.  If absences are not explained they appear as an indication of weak commitment.</p>
    <p><strong><em>There are no bill adjustments for missed classes.</em></strong></p>
    <p>Student participation is expected at all scheduled group classes.  Skill development, refined musicianship and recital preparation are goals of these classes.  Additional to faithful participation in all classes of the semester, students must participate in at least three of the last four group classes in order to perform the group pieces with his/her class.  Students should expect to perform in the recital only pieces that are well polished and at least two pieces prior to their current lesson piece.</p>
